Got it — that changes the game significantly.

If all 15+ services are stateful + critical (financial domain), then a simple “pilot stateless → expand” won’t work. You need a zero/near-zero downtime, data-consistent, reversible migration strategy.

I’ll give you:
	1.	Real-world strategy (used in banks)
	2.	Phased migration plan (service-by-service but safe)
	3.	Architecture Decision Records (ADR)
	4.	Concrete execution for first service

⸻

🧠 Core Strategy (For Critical Stateful Systems)

You are not “migrating apps” →
👉 You are migrating data + traffic + consistency guarantees

✅ Golden approach:

Strangler Fig + Parallel Run + Data Sync

⸻

🧱 Target Architecture (Low infra, high reliability)
	•	Kubernetes → Amazon EKS
	•	GitOps → Argo CD
	•	DB → Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL
	•	MQ → Amazon MQ (or self-managed if strict latency/HA needed)
	•	Monitoring → Amazon Managed Service for Prometheus

👉 Minimal infra ops, maximum reliability

⸻

⚠️ Key Constraints (Financial Systems)

You must guarantee:
	•	No data loss
	•	No duplicate processing
	•	Message ordering (RabbitMQ)
	•	Transaction integrity (Postgres)
	•	Full rollback capability

⸻

🚀 PHASED MIGRATION PLAN (SAFE + REVERSIBLE)

⸻

🧩 Phase 0: Foundation (Do NOT skip)

1. Network
	•	Site-to-Site VPN (minimum)
	•	Ideally Direct Connect (later)

2. Identity & Security
	•	IAM roles
	•	Secrets → AWS Secrets Manager
	•	TLS everywhere

3. Observability baseline
	•	Logs + metrics unified

⸻

🧪 Phase 1: Shadow Environment (CRITICAL STEP)

👉 This is where most teams fail.

You will:
	•	Deploy full stack in AWS (EKS)
	•	Keep ON-PREM as primary
	•	AWS runs in shadow mode

⸻

What runs in AWS:
	•	All 15 services deployed via Argo CD
	•	Connected to:
	•	Replica DB
	•	Replica MQ

⸻

Data Replication

PostgreSQL:
	•	Use logical replication → RDS
	•	Or AWS DMS (continuous sync)

RabbitMQ:

Options:
	1.	Federation plugin
	2.	Shovel plugin
	3.	Dual publishing (best for control)

⸻

Result:

AWS is fully live but NOT serving users

⸻

🔁 Phase 2: Parallel Run (Dual Processing)

👉 Both environments process same data

Flow:

Producer → RabbitMQ (on-prem)
        → replicated to AWS MQ

Both:
- On-prem services process
- AWS services process


⸻

Validation layer

You MUST build:
	•	Data reconciliation service (you already have XML recon 👀)
	•	Compare:
	•	DB outputs
	•	Events processed
	•	API responses

⸻

🔐 This ensures:
	•	Functional parity
	•	No hidden bugs

⸻

🚦 Phase 3: Controlled Cutover (Service-by-Service)

Now we migrate ONE service at a time, but safely.

⸻

🔹 Migration Pattern per Service

Step 1: Freeze writes (short window)
	•	Pause producer OR queue

Step 2: Sync final data
	•	Ensure DB fully synced

Step 3: Switch dependency

Example:
	•	Service-A now uses:
	•	RDS instead of on-prem DB
	•	AWS MQ instead of on-prem MQ

⸻

Step 4: Route traffic
	•	Shift traffic to AWS service
	•	Keep on-prem as standby

⸻

Step 5: Monitor
	•	Errors
	•	Data mismatch
	•	Latency

⸻

Step 6: Keep rollback ready

If failure:
👉 switch traffic back instantly

⸻

🔁 Phase 4: Dependency Migration

After services:

⸻

🐘 PostgreSQL
	•	Promote RDS as primary
	•	On-prem becomes fallback (optional)

⸻

🐇 RabbitMQ
	•	Move producers → AWS MQ
	•	Decommission federation

⸻

📊 Prometheus
	•	Switch fully to managed

⸻

🧾 ARCHITECTURE DECISION RECORDS (ADR)

⸻

🧾 ADR-001: Use Managed Kubernetes

Decision: Use Amazon EKS

Why:
	•	Reduce control plane ops
	•	HA by default

Tradeoff:
	•	Slightly higher cost vs self-managed

⸻

🧾 ADR-002: Use Managed PostgreSQL

Decision: Use Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL

Why:
	•	Automated backups
	•	Multi-AZ
	•	Patching handled

Risk:
	•	Vendor lock-in

⸻

🧾 ADR-003: RabbitMQ Strategy

Decision: Prefer Amazon MQ

Alternative:
	•	Self-managed on EKS

Why:
	•	Less ops
	•	Built-in HA

⸻

🧾 ADR-004: Migration Approach

Decision: Shadow + Parallel Run + Gradual Cutover

Why:
	•	Zero downtime
	•	Data validation

⸻

🧾 ADR-005: GitOps

Decision: Continue with Argo CD

Why:
	•	Consistency across environments
	•	Auditability (important for finance)

⸻

🧪 FIRST SERVICE MIGRATION (DETAILED)

Let’s simulate Service-A (critical + stateful)

⸻

🔹 Step 1: Deploy in AWS
	•	Deploy via ArgoCD into EKS
	•	Config:
	•	Still pointing to ON-PREM DB + MQ

⸻

🔹 Step 2: Enable DB replication
	•	On-prem → RDS (continuous)

⸻

🔹 Step 3: Enable MQ replication
	•	Federation or dual publish

⸻

🔹 Step 4: Shadow mode
	•	Service runs in AWS
	•	Not exposed to users

⸻

🔹 Step 5: Parallel validation
	•	Compare:
	•	DB writes
	•	Messages processed

⸻

🔹 Step 6: Cutover
	•	Stop writes briefly
	•	Switch:
	•	DB → RDS
	•	MQ → AWS MQ
	•	Route traffic → AWS

⸻

🔹 Step 7: Post-check
	•	Validate:
	•	Transactions
	•	Message processing
	•	No duplication

⸻

🔹 Step 8: Keep fallback
	•	On-prem still intact

⸻

💰 COST OPTIMIZATION (IMPORTANT)

Since everything is stateful:

Use:
	•	Small EKS node groups initially
	•	Scale gradually
	•	Graviton instances (cheaper)

Avoid:
	•	Over-provisioning DB
	•	Too many NAT gateways

⸻

⚠️ HARDEST PROBLEMS (Be ready)
	1.	RabbitMQ ordering issues
	2.	DB replication lag
	3.	Split-brain scenarios
	4.	Hidden service dependencies

⸻

🧠 Reality Check

This is NOT a 2–3 week job.

For financial systems:
👉 Expect 2–4 months minimum

